The paper deals with the problem of delivering dependent sources across a network of noisy, discrete, memoryless channels. This problem is a classic one in information theory and falls under the category of network information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. 

The paper also deals with wireline networks, which suggests that it may fall under the sub-category of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). 

The paper discusses the achievable distortion matrices for delivering sources across a network, which suggests that it may also fall under the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). 

The paper deals with dependent sources, which suggests that it may also fall under the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). 

Finally, the paper discusses the separation of source-network coding and channel coding, which suggests that it may also fall under the sub-category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
